  "prompt": "What is human right?",
  "response": "Human rights are fundamental rights and freedoms that belong to every individual, regardless of nationality, ethnicity, gender, religion, or any other status. They are inherent to all human beings and are meant to protect people from injustice, discrimination, and abuse. Human rights are typically universal, inalienable, indivisible, and interdependent\u2014meaning they apply to everyone, cannot be taken away, are all equally important, and are interconnected.\n\nThe concept of human rights is rooted in various philosophical, religious, and cultural traditions and has been formalized through international agreements and legal systems. The **Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR)**, adopted by the United Nations in 1948, is one of the most significant documents outlining these rights. It includes civil, political, economic, social, and cultural rights, such as:\n\n1. **Civil and Political Rights**:\n   - Right to life and liberty\n   - Freedom from torture and slavery\n   - Freedom of expression and opinion\n   - Right to a fair trial\n   - Right to participate in government and free elections\n\n2. **Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights**:\n   - Right to work, education, and healthcare\n   - Right to an adequate standard of living\n   - Right to participate in cultural life\n   - Right to social security\n\n3. **Collective Rights**:\n   - Right to development\n   - Right to a healthy environment\n   - Rights of indigenous peoples\n\nHuman rights are enforced through national laws, international treaties, and institutions like the United Nations, regional human rights courts, and non-governmental organizations (NGOs). While progress has been made, challenges remain in ensuring these rights are universally respected and protected.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
